{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_019NzTWANzfVdUrLa3Dq8kuS","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me analyze the task. I need to deploy a 3-node Elasticsearch cluster in the `elasticsearch` namespace using native Kubernetes resources (no operators or CRDs). Let me plan the resources I need to create:\n\n1. **ConfigMap** - for Elasticsearch configuration\n2. **StatefulSet** - for the 3 Elasticsearch nodes\n3. **Service (headless)** - for pod-to-pod communication (es-transport)\n4. **Service (es-http)** - for external access over HTTPS (port 9200)\n5. **PodDisruptionBudget** - optional but good practice\nI need to account for the existing TLS secret with certificate and key files, plus the elastic password secret. For ES 8.x with security enabled by default, I'll configure TLS on the HTTP port, set up cluster discovery for the three nodes, and inject the password from the secret.\n\nFor the StatefulSet, the pods will be named elasticsearch-0 through elasticsearch-2, so I'll use those names for cluster initialization and discovery. Since only the HTTP TLS secret is provided, I'll reuse that certificate for both HTTP and transport layer communication rather than generating additional certificates. Configuring the Elasticsearch security settings...\n\nI'm concerned about hostname verification with the HTTP certificate being used for transport, so I'll disable verification or set it to certificate mode. For the elastic user password, I can leverage the `ELASTIC_PASSWORD` environment variable during initial bootstrap, which should work fine since this is a fresh namespace setup.\n\nNow I'm planning out the full Kubernetes manifest structure with a ConfigMap for the elasticsearch.yml configuration and a headless Service for cluster discovery on port 9300.\n\nI need to handle the node name dynamically using the downward API to inject the pod name as an environment variable, then reference it in the elasticsearch.yml config as a variable substitution.\n\nWriting the manifest... Configuring transport layer security...\n\nBut I'm realizing the certificate might not have the right SANs for inter-node communication using the headless service DNS names, so the `es-http-tls` secret may not work as-is for transport TLS.\n\nI'll set `verification_mode: none` for transport to avoid hostname verification failures while still encrypting the traffic—this is acceptable for an internal cluster. Now I need to write out the full StatefulSet manifest with the environment variables, downward API references for the node name, TLS certificate mounts, ConfigMap mounts, persistent volume claims, and resource limits. I'll also make sure to set the `ELASTIC_PASSWORD` environment variable from the secret for initial bootstrap in Elasticsearch 8.x. Elasticsearch needs `vm.max_map_count` set to at least 262144, which I can handle with a privileged init container that runs the sysctl command. Now I'm putting together the complete manifest with the ConfigMap for the Elasticsearch configuration.\n\nWriting config YAML... Writing Kubernetes manifests... Configuring the readiness probe to check cluster health via HTTPS, setting resource requests and limits for memory and CPU, defining the config and certificate volumes from ConfigMap and Secret, and creating a persistent volume claim template for 10Gi of storage. environment variables should expand properly when the shell executes the command. Now I'm thinking through the PodDisruptionBudget configuration to ensure at least two replicas stay available during disruptions.\n\nFor cluster formation, the headless service DNS will resolve to individual pod IPs, allowing the nodes to discover each other through `discovery.seed_hosts`. I should finalize the complete manifest with all these pieces together. For a multi-node cluster in Kubernetes, I need to set `cluster.initial_master_nodes` to bootstrap the cluster properly, and while it's technically meant for initial setup only, keeping it in the ConfigMap for a StatefulSet is fine. The data path defaults to `/usr/share/elasticsearch/data` which aligns with my volume mount. I'm planning to create a complete manifest with a ConfigMap for the Elasticsearch config, a headless Service for pod discovery, an HTTP Service for external access, a PodDisruptionBudget, and a StatefulSet with three replicas. I should also decide whether to explicitly set `node.roles` or let nodes default to having all roles.\n\nNow I'm writing the manifest and setting up the readiness probe. I'll use a curl command to check the cluster health endpoint with authentication, verifying that the response is either a 200 or 408 status code.\n\nWriting manifest YAML... Completing the transport layer SSL configuration with certificate verification and paths, then defining a headless Kubernetes service that exposes both the transport port for node communication and the HTTP port for client access.\n\nNow I'm setting up an additional HTTP service for external access, configuring a pod disruption budget to maintain at least two replicas during cluster maintenance, and beginning the StatefulSet definition that will manage the Elasticsearch cluster with the headless service for stable network identities.\n\nConfiguring the StatefulSet replicas and pod template... Finishing the volume mounts and setting up the persistent storage configuration with a 10Gi claim, then I'm thinking through security considerations like the privileged init container for `vm.max_map_count` and potential PSP restrictions that might need addressing.\n\nNow I'm weighing whether to use the `ELASTIC_PASSWORD` environment variable to explicitly set the elastic user's password on first boot, since ES 8.x will generate a random one if not specified. I'm also considering whether enrollment tokens are needed for this manual TLS setup, and thinking about transport layer security configuration—whether to use certificate files directly in the config or set up a keystore.\n\nBefore applying the manifest, I should verify the cluster has a default storage class available for the PVCs, and check the current namespace state. I'm also planning to disable auto-enrollment with `xpack.security.enrollment.enabled: false` since we're handling TLS and security manually, and I need to configure memory locking settings.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":11681,"cache_read_input_tokens":16950,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":11681},"output_tokens":7,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"b46e79cf-3f07-46ac-a7cf-24c58627c257","uuid":"d633a67d-5e4d-40a0-9acc-bdc228d8ca49","request_id":"req_011CcLxf8XBinAMdnJnutrJe"}
